I have kernel of the form:

```{C}
\\ x, y, z = ... \\ read from global memory

double res;
switch(blockIdx.y){
    case 0:
        res = x * y;
        break;
    case 1:
        res = y * z;
        break;
    ...
}

\\ ... = res \\ write to global memory
```
Number of cases goes to ~50, all labeled as consecutive (!) integers starting from 0.

When I make .ptx it shows that switch-case is expanded into conditional branches, and it feels.
The thing is even though branch divergence never occur (and cannot occur due to construction), the sheer number of comparisons degrades performance.     

What I really would like to achieve is uniform jumps. One way I see is to separate body of each case in function, construct array of functional pointers, and then (in kernel) select by blockIdx.y. On the downside, functions are very small (handful multiplications at most), so overhead of a function call itself would be noticeable. 

Is there any way around it?

**Edit.**

Opted for defining each case as a separate device function:
```
__device__ double func0(const double x, const double y, const double z) { return x * y; }
```
and placing array of functional pointers to constant memory:
```
__constant__ double (*const fptr[]) (const double, const double, const double) = { func0, func1, ... } 
```
So that in kernel call selection and application of function merge with write to global memory:
```
... = fptr[blockIdx.y](x, y, z);
```
Which results in a much cleaner code, and apparently no conditional branching. However, witnessed neither performance gain, nor degrade, which makes me wonder whether the code executed on GPU in the end (with blockIdx.y substituted) is substantially different for these two approaches.

